5742686739787916546.text:
At the Museum"

I went to the "Museum der Bildenden Künste" (Museum of fine arts) last week to see an exhibition on Dutch paintings from the 17th century. While I had seen other exhibitions there before, I had never taken the time to explore the museum more thoroughly. The museum was "newly" constructed in the late 1990s (opened in 2004) and its design is certainly controversial. Especially if you consider that most of the buildings on the side of the Katharinenstraße are historic buildings from the 17th/18th century (see my recent post on the Fregehaus: http://mellimage.blogspot.de/2012/05/p-52-yellow-and-blue.html).
Be that as it may, if you like modern architecture, the building is certainly fascinating (the museum was desgined by the Berlin Based architects Berlin-based architects Hufnagel / Puetz / Rafaelian). Huge/ high spaces, materials mixed together - cold grey stone, warm wood, glass. This all gives it a very interesting feel and I am certain to return back to it. I saw this scene and was quite intrigued by the pattern the light painted into the wall (it reminded me to an image by +G Dan Mitchell ) The installation you see before the window is called "Trillerpfeifen und Ghettoblaster" (Whistles and Ghetto Blasters) by Bogomir Eckert. Hope you enjoy it.

5745381725947469474.text:
Annular Solar Eclipse at 7:35 JST on 21 May 2012.

It's a miracle ring what celestial mechanics makes for a few minitues of the centuries at the specific place.

The celestial ring hovered above dark fast-fleeting clouds. It looks like Japanese Sumi-e, ink-and-wash painting.

The Earth revolves about the sun yearly and the Moon revolves about the Earth monthly. So if the Moon were in a circular orbit close enough to the Earth and in the same orbital plane, there would be total solar eclipses every single month. However, the Moon's orbit is angled at more than 5 degrees to the earth's orbit around the Sun so its shadow at new moon often misses the Earth. This factor makes an Eclipse rare phenomenon.

At Tokyo, the last Annular Eclipse occurred on 8 September 1839 (5:28-5:30). This time it occurred on 21 May 2012 (7:32-7:37). Next time it will occur on 8 April 2312 (6:56-6:59). I can’t see it in my life again, at least, in Tokyo.

I'll alternate pics between Yellowstone and Zion, so this is the first Yellowstone pic.

Not photoshopped by the way. The herds of Bison in Lamar Valley were huge, several thousand, much larger than in Hayden Valley. You don't get close to them as much as they get close to you, if they decide to cross the street in front of you either jump in your car or stay still. They came as close as 3 or 4 feet sometimes.

I shot a lot of pics towards the sunset, letting the light flare inside the lens to add a natural vignette and glow. I have some wider pics of the herds, but I liked the isolation in this male bison. All colors are natural here.

Equipment and settings:
Canon 5D Mark II
ISO 1250, f/5.6, 1/800s
Canon EF 100-400mm f/4.5-5.6 L IS USM @400mm
Gitzo GT1542T tripod
Markins Q3T ballhead and plate

5796027804492451506.text:
Fog City clouds above Golden Gate Bridge

Lesson learned in getting what you weren't looking for...

Hiked 2 miles up and down the coast looking for a great sunset shot of the bridge. With the clouds looming overhead, I muttered ugly statements at the miserable light and started to hike back up the trail to the car.

I took one last look back at the bridge before heading up over a ridge, and thought the light on the clouds looked interesting. After honing in on this composition for a while, realized there may be something there.

Lesson learned that even normally miserable conditions can reveal something you didn't know to look for. If fact, I keep learning this lesson as a handful of my best-ever photos have come at sunset but overcast conditions, but had an element that made it worth it.

5831170928439193442.text:
Now that my new website is online, I am excited to start sharing my spectacular new images from my adventures during the second half of 2012!

In July and August, Tony Wu and I co-lead our first Megaptera Mania Tour with 6 wonderful clients. After the Tonga portion of tour was over, I spent a second week whale watching with just 2 of our clients. (I should mention that anyone who travels with me for any length of time also becomes a close friend.) This humpback whale calf seemingly levitating is my most interesting image.

We spent the better part of the morning following this mother, calf, and escort. They basically did nothing for hours, but we stayed with them because there weren’t a lot of other whale options around at the time. However, we could sense that something was going to happen, and eventually the 3 whales exploded from the water in what can only be described as a goodbye greeting to each other. This breaching behavior lasted for about 15 minutes, during which we frantically tried to point our cameras in the right direction as they continuously erupted from the water. After the whales settled down, I was flabbergasted to discover this breaching calf photo while reviewing my images. Incredible! I created this image using my Canon 7D and 70-200mm f2.8 IS II lens and processed the RAW file using Aperture 3 and Photoshop CS6. The original image was a little tight on the right side, but since it was just empty background I slightly expanded it to allow for more space.

5833197775455287490.text:
Last Light on The Mara

This image was made at the end of a magnificent day in Maasai Mara, Kenya, and depicts the symbiosis that exists in the animal kingdom. These Oxpecker birds live most of their lives on the giraffe; they were startled into flight by the giraffe's movement, but quickly resettled on the giraffe's neck for their continued mutual symbiotic relationship.

Nothing in the universe exists alone. Every drop of water, every human being, all creatures in the web of life, and all ideas in the web of knowledge are part of an immense, evolving, dynamic whole as old, and as young, as the universe itself.  ~   "Symbiosis"  (1982)

The Plus One Collection project by +Ivan Makarov is an amazing cooperation between the talented community on Google+ and others in the world in producing a published photographic collection and helping others to also experience the joy of photography through this year's cooperative program in Kenya. I'm honored to be a part of this group by contributing this work to the publication. Thank you to Ivan Makarov and others in our wonderful G+ community who have dedicated their valuable time and expertise to this project.

5867606734621958834.text:
You can barely see it from the "stream" view - I highly encourage you to click on this image and use your scroll wheel to zoom in - you'll see some awesome colour in the center of this snowflake. :)

The book project is 115% funded! Interested in hundreds of these images in a 300pg hardcover book? Check out the project, only two weeks left to make it even better! http://igg.me/at/skycrystals/

The colour you see in this snowflake is caused by optical interference. The same optical principals create colour in soap bubbles, and it's also used in fancy lens coatings to remove flare, etc.

You'll also see, when zoomed in, that some of the branches are growing on top of the regular branches, giving depth to the detail. The area around the center is also interesting, reminding me of an ornate glass serving dish.

Aren't snowflakes fun? :)

5872751517702176818.text:
Lupine Dreams - Folsom, California

www.tactilephoto.com

After seeing +Willie Huang beautiful image "Purple Magic" I knew I had to make a trip out to Folsom Lake.  It was windy, not a cloud in the sky and from what I had heard - the lupine were past their prime. I knew if I didn't go, I would kick myself for the next 5-10 years waiting for another super bloom.  Needless to say, the photography gods smiled upon me last night.  Our first colorful sunset in weeks, not a hint of wind and the lupine (while faded somewhat) were still in pretty good shape.

#tactilephoto   #landscapephotography   #lupine   #sunset   #folsom   #california

5905875684300335138.text:
I was lucky enough to be selected to take part in +Beth Akerman's Artist Photography Mentorship. The reason I wanted to take part in this mentorship was to push myself to try new things. This week I had some fun with processing my photo's in ways that I never would.

For this photo I played with all kinds of sliders in Lightroom to see what they would do. This particular shot is one that I really like the processing I did (yes, I'm tooting my own horn.) It's not something I would normally do because I'm more of a realist with my photography, but I really like how it turned out. :-)
